[Crickets chirping]

173
00:09:41,181 --> 00:09:45,185
[Gasping breaths]

174
00:09:47,143 --> 00:09:48,057
Hey.

175
00:09:50,190 --> 00:09:53,106
I can't sleep.

176
00:09:53,236 --> 00:09:56,936
Uh, yeah, me neither.
I thought you'd like some tea?

177
00:09:57,066 --> 00:09:58,807
Do you want some?

178
00:10:01,027 --> 00:10:01,984
Sure.

179
00:10:09,557 --> 00:10:12,212
You and Kenny make
a really cute couple.

180
00:10:12,342 --> 00:10:14,388
Oh, uh, no,
we're just...

181
00:10:14,518 --> 00:10:15,868
We're just friends.

182
00:10:15,998 --> 00:10:17,565
Why?

183
00:10:17,696 --> 00:10:21,003
He's really sweet,
and he loves you.

184
00:10:21,134 --> 00:10:23,484
It's complicated.

185
00:10:23,615 --> 00:10:25,268
How?

186
00:10:25,399 --> 00:10:28,315
Well, 'cause I...
[Sighing]

187
00:10:28,445 --> 00:10:31,448
...have somebody at home.

188
00:10:31,579 --> 00:10:35,409
At least I think she's...
still... waiting.

189
00:10:37,237 --> 00:10:38,412
What's her name?

190
00:10:40,022 --> 00:10:42,198
Mariel.

191
00:10:42,329 --> 00:10:45,245
-Were you married?
-Engaged.

192
00:10:45,375 --> 00:10:49,510
I wonder sometimes,
actually all the time, uh,

193
00:10:49,641 --> 00:10:54,167
what it must be like for her,
thinking I, uh, abandoned her.

194
00:10:54,297 --> 00:10:57,083
Um, how about you?

195
00:10:57,213 --> 00:10:59,520
Do you have
anybody back at home?

196
00:10:59,651 --> 00:11:01,478
No.

197
00:11:01,609 --> 00:11:04,003
I... I was with someone,

198
00:11:04,133 --> 00:11:08,311
but he wasn't...

199
00:11:08,442 --> 00:11:13,099
It's better that
he's not around anymore.

200
00:11:13,229 --> 00:11:16,537
It's just me and Nathan now.

201
00:11:16,668 --> 00:11:20,584
He's all
I've got in the world.

202
00:11:20,715 --> 00:11:24,284
Before we got
stuck here, I, um...

203
00:11:24,414 --> 00:11:28,375
Things weren't
really very good for me.

204
00:11:28,505 --> 00:11:31,030
Nathan was
the one who saved me.

205
00:11:33,293 --> 00:11:35,034
Can I ask you something?

206
00:11:35,164 --> 00:11:37,601
Yeah. Sure.

207
00:11:37,732 --> 00:11:41,388
If there was
something you could do,

208
00:11:41,518 --> 00:11:46,175
something that would
let you see Mariel again...

209
00:11:47,699 --> 00:11:51,441
something that would let
everyone here go home,

210
00:11:51,572 --> 00:11:55,010
even if it was something bad,

211
00:11:55,141 --> 00:11:56,577
would you do it?

212
00:11:57,317 --> 00:11:59,754
Wait,
what are you talking about?

213
00:11:59,885 --> 00:12:04,628
I wonder sometimes...
about this place,

214
00:12:04,759 --> 00:12:08,067
what it means...

215
00:12:08,197 --> 00:12:10,112
why we're here.

216
00:12:11,635 --> 00:12:15,248
If someone came up to you
right now and said,

217
00:12:15,378 --> 00:12:18,120
"Do this one bad thing

218
00:12:18,251 --> 00:12:22,081
and everyone
gets to go home,"

219
00:12:22,211 --> 00:12:24,213
would you do it?

220
00:12:24,344 --> 00:12:27,739
Well, we're...

221
00:12:27,869 --> 00:12:30,350
we're speaking
hypothetically, right?

222
00:12:30,480 --> 00:12:31,351
Yeah.

223
00:12:31,481 --> 00:12:32,352
Okay.

224
00:12:32,482 --> 00:12:33,570
Of course.

225
00:12:33,701 --> 00:12:35,224
[Chuckles]
Okay.

226
00:12:35,355 --> 00:12:36,486
Uh...

227
00:12:39,185 --> 00:12:42,666
I mean...

228
00:12:42,797 --> 00:12:45,234
Yeah, I'd, um...

229
00:12:45,365 --> 00:12:48,237
I'd do anything
to see her again and...

230
00:12:48,368 --> 00:12:49,761
And hey, I mean,

231
00:12:49,891 --> 00:12:51,719
if that meant everybody else
got to go home too,

232
00:12:51,850 --> 00:12:54,678
then, I think
that's a lot of good

233
00:12:54,809 --> 00:12:58,030
for one bad thing.

234
00:13:00,772 --> 00:13:01,990
Yeah.

235
00:13:10,346 --> 00:13:11,260
Hmm.

236
00:13:11,391 --> 00:13:13,610
[Exhales]

237
00:13:13,741 --> 00:13:15,221
Tell me you
figured it out.

238
00:13:15,351 --> 00:13:17,310
Oh, I-I did.

239
00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:19,573
And the answer is 12.

240
00:13:19,703 --> 00:13:22,750
[Chuckles]
Okay.

241
00:13:22,881 --> 00:13:25,535
All right,
let's go over this again.

242
00:13:28,538 --> 00:13:32,455
Everyone enters from different
parts of the country,

243
00:13:32,586 --> 00:13:34,893
on different roads,
in different places,

244
00:13:35,023 --> 00:13:37,243
and they all, presumably,
see the same tree,

245
00:13:37,373 --> 00:13:38,722
same crows.

246
00:13:38,853 --> 00:13:40,463
Jim, Jim...

247
00:13:40,594 --> 00:13:44,641
everyone here has asked the same
question over and over again.

248
00:13:44,772 --> 00:13:47,601
How does writing
them on the wall

249
00:13:47,731 --> 00:13:49,168
going to make
any difference?

250
00:13:49,298 --> 00:13:51,561
Because...

251
00:13:51,692 --> 00:13:54,086
There are plenty of things in
the world that don't make sense.

252
00:13:54,216 --> 00:13:55,391
Yeah.

253
00:13:55,522 --> 00:13:57,567
Something here
is missing.

254
00:13:58,742 --> 00:14:01,180
We just can't see it yet.

255
00:14:01,310 --> 00:14:02,442
But we will.

256
00:14:02,572 --> 00:14:05,488
Well, there's a question
we haven't asked.

257
00:14:17,761 --> 00:14:19,285
No.

258
00:14:19,415 --> 00:14:22,375
Why not?

259
00:14:23,071 --> 00:14:26,205
Because it's crazy.
[Sighing]

260
00:14:30,470 --> 00:14:32,341
I don't want
to know the answer.

261
00:14:38,826 --> 00:14:41,263
You sure you're not hungry?
I was gonna make some oatmeal.

